<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-04-07T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-04-07T16:00:00-05:00" n="203" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d203">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">504.418A2/248: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Minister in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Diekema</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-04-07T16:00:00-05:00">April 7, 1930—4
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>25. For Miller. Your 46, Conference No. 13.<note n="8" xml:id="d203fn8"><hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_211">p.
                                211</ref>.</note> We think you should refuse to sign convention and
                            make statement to the effect indicated by you. We do not think you
                            should sign with reservations. Proposed Articles 1 and 2 seem to us more
                            objectionable even than you indicate.</p>
                        <p>Your 17.<note n="9" xml:id="d203fn9"><hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_213">p. 213</ref>.</note> We think it better to say
                            at the conference that your delegation has recommended against signature
                            and you do not expect signature even if the general clause permits
                            signature until end 1930.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Cotton</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>